etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in The Siege of Jerusalem. From un- + lap

definitions: To open up, fold back, or remove (a covering, wrapping, etc.); to spread open or unfold (something folded or rolled up, especially (in early use) a letter or other document). Also without object or reflexive: to become spread open or unfolded.

To uncover (something) by removing a cloth, covering, or wrapping; to remove the wrapping or covering from; especially to remove clothing from (a person, oneself, a corpse, the area of a wound, etc.).
